->Array is a pointer=pointer arithmetic(++,--) on array(see coding notes)
->To calculate the array memory reservation=int a[30];
since int is 4bytes =4*30; so answer is 120 bytes
->we can also subtract onepointer from another 
->we can aslo compare two pointers(see the notes)
TRAVERSING AN ARRAY:-
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int aadhar[5];
    
    int *ptr = aadhar; //same as &aadhar[0] u know this write by default pointer points to the first element in the array
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        printf("%d index : ", i);
        scanf("%d", (ptr + i)); // here we can do this also that is using the &aadhar[i]
    }
    printf("\n"); 
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        printf("%d index = %d\n", i, *(ptr + i)); // and here we can simply do aadhar[i]
    }
    return 0;
} see here output will be 0 index : 4
1 index : 5
2 index : 7
3 index : 5
4 index : 4

0 index = 4
1 index = 5
2 index = 7
3 index = 5
4 index = 4

ARRAYS AS FUNCTION ARGUMENT:- 
declaration:1) void num(int a[]//no need to specify the size it can be of any ,int n//so we use another varaible to declare the size)
2)void num(int *a,int n)
num(a//this also means that&a[0] so this will get stored in the *a,n);//function call 
